Question 2 a) full inde

inde_fun = function(n=100, mu1=0,sd1=1,a=0,b=0,c=0,d=0,e=0){

  x1 = rnorm(n, mean= mu1, sd = sd1)

  mu2 = a + b*x1 # b = x2Rx1
  sd2 = 1
  x2 = rnorm(n, mean= mu2, sd = sd2) 

  mu3 = c + d*x1 + e*x2 #d = x1Rx3, e = x2Rx3
  sd3 = 1
  x3 = rnorm(n, mean= mu3, sd = sd3)
  
  plot(x1~x2)
  plot(x3~x2)
  plot(x1~x3)

}

inde_fun(n=100)

The general lack of overlapping points and seemingly random spread throughout the graphs, suggest to me that this is indeed full independence. b) partial inde

inde_fun = function(n=100, mu1=0,sd1=1,a=0,b=0,c=0,d=0,e=0){

  x1 = rnorm(n, mean= mu1, sd = sd1)

  mu2 = a + b*x1 # b = x2Rx1
  sd2 = 1
  x2 = rnorm(n, mean= mu2, sd = sd2) 

  mu3 = c + d*x1 + e*x2 #d = x1Rx3, e = x2Rx3
  sd3 = 1
  x3 = rnorm(n, mean= mu3, sd = sd3)
  
  plot(x1~x2)
  plot(x3~x2)
  plot(x1~x3)

}

inde_fun(n=100,e=6)

(x1 and x2) and (x1 and x3) seem to be independent, with random spreads and little overlap or direction however, x2 and x3 seem to be strongly correlated, with a positive relationship (slope). Many overlapping points, more like a line.

  1. marginal inde

  x3 = rnorm(n, mean= mu3, sd = sd3)
  
  plot(x1~x2)
  plot(x3~x2)
  plot(x1~x3)

}

inde_fun(n=100,b=-6)

The first graph relates x1 and x2 and shows a negative slope, lots of dots overlapping and forming (almost) a line. This is different from the other two graphs which seems to be randomly placed dots spread not really overlapping, so it seems x2Rx1, but not(x1Rx3 or x2Rx3).

  1. conditional inde

  plot(x1~x3)

}

inde_fun(n=100,d=10,e=10)

The second and third graphs represent a positive potential relation between x1 and x3 also between x2 and x3, but there does not seem to be a relation between x1 and x2. Looks like we have conditional independence of x1 and x2 given x3.

  1. full dep
inde_fun = function(n=100, mu1=0,sd1=1,a=0,b=0,c=0,d=0,e=0){

  x1 = rnorm(n, mean= mu1, sd = sd1)

  mu2 = a + b*x1 # b = x2Rx1
  sd2 = 1
  x2 = rnorm(n, mean= mu2, sd = sd2) 

  mu3 = c + d*x1 + e*x2 #d = x1Rx3, e = x2Rx3
  sd3 = 1
  x3 = rnorm(n, mean= mu3, sd = sd3)
  
  plot(x1~x2)
  plot(x3~x2)
  plot(x1~x3)

}

inde_fun(n=100,b=4,d=6,e=8)

Full dependence! We can clearly tell all of the graphs, are positively sloped, and suggest a relation between each of the variables. The spread is tight and forms a line for all of our graphs here.
